  body: "Tarotic Introduction Tarotic is a small conlang with around 150 words. The core of Tarotic is a set of 22 essential words, based on the Major Arcana of Tarot. These words are usually used as adjectives, but can sometimes be used as another part of speech. Each of these words represents a concept associated with its corresponding Major Arcana, and their spellings are derived from various languages, such as Latin, Arabic, Slavic, and Russian. The language is called Tarotic because it is based on the Tarot Cards. Concept Overall, Tarotic is a unique and creative conlang with a rich system of words and grammar based on the concepts of the Tarot. While it may have a small lexicon, each word is multifunctional and has a strong connection to its corresponding Major Arcana. Phonetics Tarotic has five vowels: Vowel Pronunciation a /a/ e /e/ i /i/ o /o/ u /u/ Tarotic also has the following consonants: Consonant Pronunciation s /s/ w /w/ l,r /l/ f,v /f/ g /g/ h /h/ k,c /k/ j /j/ n /n/ m /m/ b /b/ p /p/ z /z/ x /ks/ sh /Êƒ/ Grammar Word Order Tarotic is a verb-second language, similar to German and Dutch, which means that the verb is usually placed in the second position in a sentence. In Tarotic, the last-used verb is always placed at the end of the sentence. The word order for noun phrases is also strict, with the modifier (adjective) always coming before the noun it modifies. The basic sentence structure in Tarotic is as follows: Speaker-verb-direct object-indirect object-[verb2]\u0026hellip; Nouns Nouns that do not end with -o for some reason should be capitalized(including pronouns). Adjectives Tarotic is also a postpositive adjective language, which means that adjectives are placed after the nouns they modify. To avoid confusion, restrictive adjectives should always be connected to the nouns they modify with a hyphen. For example: \u0026ldquo;The strong man\u0026rdquo; would be translated as \u0026ldquo;Nere-forna orano\u0026rdquo; in Tarotic. Verbs Verbs in Tarotic are indicated by the ending vowel -e. The final verb in a sentence must end with -n. Tarotic has a small set of basic words, such as \u0026ldquo;to eat\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;make\u0026rdquo;), \u0026ldquo;to say\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;sire\u0026rdquo;), \u0026ldquo;to think\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;sape\u0026rdquo;), \u0026ldquo;to love\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;habe\u0026rdquo;), \u0026ldquo;to go\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;kolese\u0026rdquo;), and \u0026ldquo;to be strong\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;forne\u0026rdquo;). These words may be derived from the 22 essential words. Contexts Tarotic does not have an objective case for pronouns, so context is used to determine their function in a sentence. That-clause That-clause can be described with Vu. For example: I need a book that is written in Tarotic. / Ame note asefiro vu sude de Tarotic mean.(literal: I need a book that is of Tarotic) You can use Vu for any noun, be it a person or an object. However, you must use the word \u0026ldquo;mean\u0026rdquo; to close the that-clause to clearly indicate the end of the clause. Feelings In Tarotic, all feelings are described in a very simple way. They can be described with only two elements: \u0026ldquo;positive/negative\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;firece/temperate\u0026rdquo;. Positive and fierce: havulo (habi+vulk) Positive and temperate: halico (habi+salic) Negative and firece: mevulo (mesi+vulk) Negative and temperate: melico (mesi+salic) Part-of-speech Transformation The part of speech of a word in Tarotic can be modified by adding a certain vowel to the end: Vowel Part of Speech -a adjective -e verb -o noun -i adverb -u others There are some exceptions to this rule, such as pronouns, which do not change their form. Pronouns Tarotic is a synthetic language, meaning that words do not conjugate based on pronouns. Instead, pronouns are used in their stem form and their function is determined by context. Pronouns in Tarotic are: Person Singular Plural First Ame Amen Second Ze Zem Third(person, genderless) Ore Orem He Nere Nerem She Mare Marem Third(object) Se Sem neb and maka can be used to represent manliness or femininity. Nebore=he, Makore=she\u0026hellip; Shortening, Nere/Mare. Arcanics Tarotic has a small but multifunctional vocabulary, with many of the words derived from various languages and connected to the concepts represented by their corresponding Major Arcana. They are called Arcanics. Here are a few examples: Word Translation Major Arcana Word Origin zal easygoing, lucky The Fool a coined word, but with a sound that suggests unpredictability or spontaneity bax powerful, skilled The Magician a coined word, but with a sound that suggests power or skill sir glowing, burning The High Priestess a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;sirius,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;glowing\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;burning,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest mystery or enigma maka mother The Empress the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;mother,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest femininity or maternal qualities kor heart The Emperor a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;cor,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;heart,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest authority or rulership neb cloud, wisdom The Hierophant a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;nebula,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;cloud,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest wisdom or enlightenment habi love, passion The Lovers the Arabic word for \u0026ldquo;love\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;passion\u0026rdquo; koleso wheel The Chariot the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;wheel,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest movement or transportation for strong, powerful Strength a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;fortis,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;strong\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;powerful\u0026rdquo; sap wise, enlightened The Hermit a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;sapiens,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;wise\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;enlightened\u0026rdquo; galga fate, destiny The Wheel of Fortune stems from galgalim, the wheel-looking angel mishp justice, judgment Justice the Hebrew word for \u0026ldquo;justice\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;judgment\u0026rdquo; razi reflection, contemplation The Hanged Man the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;reflection\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;contemplation\u0026rdquo; si death Death the Japanese word for \u0026ldquo;death\u0026rdquo; taon path, balance Temperance a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;tao,\u0026rdquo; the Chinese word for \u0026ldquo;path\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;way,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest balance or moderation diab devil, temptation The Devil a shortened form of \u0026ldquo;diabolus,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;devil\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;temptation\u0026rdquo; kula tower, transformation The Tower the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;tower\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;citadel\u0026rdquo; asta hope, inspiration, aspiration, optimism The Star mesi moon The Moon the Russian word for \u0026ldquo;moon\u0026rdquo; lar warmth, light The Sun a coined word, but with a sound that suggests warmth or light sud judgment, decision Judgment the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;judgment\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;decision\u0026rdquo; mir world, universe The World the Russian word for \u0026ldquo;world\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;universe\u0026rdquo; Root forms of them are without the last vowel. Note that in general, Arcanics cannot be used in the form of bare stem, unless you refer to the concept of each Arcana itself. In this case, the word should be capitalized. Detailed meanings of Arcanics Word Detailed Meaning zal new beginnings, having faith in the future, being inexperienced, not knowing what to expect, having beginner\u0026rsquo;s luck, improvisation, believing in the universe bax power, skill, transformation, creativity, manipulation, resourcefulness sir mystery, enigma, intuition, secrets, hidden knowledge, the unconscious maka femininity, maternal qualities, fertility, nurturing, caring, comfort kor authority, rulership, leadership, stability, structure neb wisdom, enlightenment, understanding, guidance, spiritual connection habi love, passion, desire, connection, commitment koleso movement, transportation, progress, change, momentum for strength, power, courage, determination, endurance sap wisdom, enlightenment, understanding, insight, introspection galga fate, destiny, the path that one is on, the circumstances that shape one\u0026rsquo;s life mishp justice, fairness, balance, truth, honor razi reflection, contemplation, introspection, self-examination, surrender si death, rebirth, transformation, change, letting go taon balance, harmony, moderation, self-control, alignment with one\u0026rsquo;s inner path diab temptation, desire, materialism, ego, attachment kula upheaval, transformation, change, destruction, chaos asta hope, inspiration, aspiration, optimism, spirituality mesi illusion, deception, fear, the unknown, the subconscious lar warmth, light, happiness, joy, success, vitality sud decisive, final, conclusive, judgmental, condemning, condemning, judgment, decision, resolution, finality, accountability mir [adj]complete, whole, unified, accomplished, global, cosmic[noun]unity, completion, wholeness, the universe, the interconnectedness of all things Adjective meanings The Fool: [adj] carefree, optimistic, open-minded, spontaneous, reckless, unaware The Magician: [adj] skilled, powerful, resourceful, manipulative, charismatic, visionary The High Priestess: [adj] mysterious, enigmatic, intuitive, secretive, all-knowing, hidden The Empress: [adj] maternal, nurturing, feminine, abundant, fertile, loving The Emperor: [adj] authoritarian, commanding, powerful, decisive, strict, ruling The Hierophant: [adj] wise, enlightened, spiritual, religious, guiding, teaching The Lovers: [adj] passionate, loving, romantic, devoted, attracted, sensual The Chariot: [adj] fast, powerful, determined, moving, driving, commanding Strength: [adj] strong, powerful, brave, determined, resilient, capable The Hermit: [adj] wise, enlightened, solitary, introspective, spiritual, reflective The Wheel of Fortune: [adj] unpredictable, changing, cyclical, fated, destined, fateful Justice: [adj] fair, impartial, just, righteous, moral, lawful The Hanged Man: [adj] suspended, sacrificed, waiting, suspended, contemplative, resigned Death: [adj] inevitable, final, transformative, ending, changing, destructive Temperance: [adj] balanced, moderate, harmonious, self-controlled, disciplined, modest The Devil: [adj] tempting, seductive, manipulative, selfish, controlling, corrupting The Tower: [adj] destructive, transformative, sudden, shocking, revealing, devastating The Star: [adj] hopeful, inspiring, shining, guiding, aspirational, visionary The Moon: [adj] mysterious, subconscious, irrational, deceptive, illusionary, primal The Sun: [adj] joyful, warm, bright, optimistic, successful, thriving Judgment: [adj] decisive, final, conclusive, judgmental, condemning, condemning The World: [adj] complete, whole, unified, accomplished, global, cosmic Minor Arcanics Tarotic Suit Origin zelm Pentacle \u0026ldquo;zemla\u0026rdquo; (derived from the Slavic word \u0026ldquo;zemlja,\u0026rdquo; which means \u0026ldquo;earth\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;soil,\u0026rdquo; and could suggest stability or abundance) vulk Wand (derived from the Slavic word \u0026ldquo;vulkan,\u0026rdquo; which means \u0026ldquo;volcano,\u0026rdquo; and could suggest fire or energy) zefir Sword (derived from the Greek word \u0026ldquo;zephyros,\u0026rdquo; which means \u0026ldquo;west wind,\u0026rdquo; and could suggest direction or progression) salic Cup derived from Croatian [Wand] The wand represents a staff or club and is associated with the element of fire. It represents passion, will, imagination, intuition, and ego. It also represents the heat, momentum, and ascendancy of a flame. [Pentacle] The pentacle represents a gold coin or talisman and signifies the \u0026ldquo;earth\u0026rdquo; element. The pentacle is often depicted as a gold coin with a pentagram within it. It represents assets, work, income, talent, status, and personal connections. [Sword] Sword represents a sword and signifies the element of \u0026ldquo;wind\u0026rdquo;. It represents objectivity, logic, thought, language, and intelligence,\u0026quot; and is interpreted with these qualities in readings. [Cup]. The cup represents the chalice and signifies the element of \u0026ldquo;water\u0026rdquo;. It represents the water nature of affection, emotion, sensitivity, passivity, love, fantasy, dreams, imagination, faith, and the unconscious. Interrogatives Tarotic also has a set of interrogative words. These words are pronounced with a sound similar to \u0026ldquo;F,\u0026rdquo; rather than the spelling \u0026ldquo;V.\u0026rdquo; Word Meaning Voru Who Vu What Volesu Where Vudu When Votu Why Veba How Origin \u0026ldquo;Who\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Voru\u0026rdquo; (using the pronoun for \u0026ldquo;he/she\u0026rdquo; to ask about a person) \u0026ldquo;What\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Vu\u0026rdquo; (using the pronoun for \u0026ldquo;it\u0026rdquo; to ask about a thing or concept) \u0026ldquo;Where\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Volesu\u0026rdquo; (using the word for \u0026ldquo;wheel\u0026rdquo; to suggest movement or location) \u0026ldquo;When\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Vudu\u0026rdquo; (using the word for \u0026ldquo;fate\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;destiny\u0026rdquo; to suggest time or timing) \u0026ldquo;Why\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Votu\u0026rdquo; (using the word for \u0026ldquo;need\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;want\u0026rdquo; to suggest motivation or purpose) \u0026ldquo;How\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Veba\u0026rdquo; (using the word for \u0026ldquo;cloud\u0026rdquo; to suggest ways or methods) Imperative You can make verbs imperative by simply changing its last vowel to -ore. For example: Astore(aste+-ore): Look! Number System Tarotic has a base-22 number system, using the 22 essential words as roots for numbers up to 22. It can count up to 21, with each number represented by adding \u0026ldquo;os\u0026rdquo; to the root form of the corresponding essential word. For example, 0 is \u0026ldquo;zalos\u0026rdquo; and 1 is \u0026ldquo;baxos\u0026rdquo;. To represent numbers larger than 22, they are simply combined, such as 23 being represented as \u0026ldquo;baxos-arcosa\u0026rdquo; (1+22). Colors Color Word Yellow Wakana Black Kulana Red Korana White Zalana Blue Astana Green Makana Vocabulary Common words Tarotic English Derived from make to eat sire to say \u0026ldquo;sir,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;glowing\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;burning\u0026rdquo; sape to think, to feel \u0026ldquo;sap,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;wise\u0026rdquo; habe to love \u0026ldquo;habi,\u0026rdquo; the Arabic word for \u0026ldquo;love\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;passion\u0026rdquo; kolese to go \u0026ldquo;koleso,\u0026rdquo; the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;wheel\u0026rdquo; forne to be strong \u0026ldquo;for,\u0026rdquo; the Latin word for \u0026ldquo;strong\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;powerful\u0026rdquo; mine to know kulane to change \u0026ldquo;kula,\u0026rdquo; the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;tower\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;citadel\u0026rdquo; aste to see, to read mesie to hear \u0026ldquo;mesi,\u0026rdquo; the Russian word for \u0026ldquo;moon\u0026rdquo; miske to give \u0026ldquo;mishp,\u0026rdquo; the Hebrew word for \u0026ldquo;justice\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;judgment\u0026rdquo; lare to take \u0026ldquo;lar,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest acquisition or possession note to need, want Temperance taon reversed pune to have derived from Indonesian punya zale to do \u0026ldquo;zal,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest action or activity sude to be \u0026ldquo;sud,\u0026rdquo; the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;judgment\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;decision\u0026rdquo; baxe to make, to create \u0026ldquo;bax,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest creativity or invention miname to learn(fruitfully know) hazelme to play, to enjoy The lovers and Pentacle kolame to write To write: \u0026ldquo;kolama\u0026rdquo; (derived from \u0026ldquo;koleso,\u0026rdquo; the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;wheel,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest movement or progression, and \u0026ldquo;maka,\u0026rdquo; the Slavic word for \u0026ldquo;mother,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest creation or nurturing) siro something derived from sir(The High Priestess). Add a nuance of mystery, enigma, or secrecy. orano-sira someone asefiro book Miscellaneous Words Word Translation of de to/towards ke if jaku but sirut not ibu with koru -m (plural) -m or sudabu and et living milaro human orano water salic A kor forake B\u0026hellip; Compared to B, A [is]\u0026hellip;(comparative) Tarotic also has words for \u0026ldquo;living beings\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;milaro\u0026rdquo;) and \u0026ldquo;human\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;orano\u0026rdquo;), as well as \u0026ldquo;water\u0026rdquo; (\u0026ldquo;salic,\u0026rdquo; derived from Croatian). Major suffixes For verbs -ame: derived from maka(The Empress). Add a nuance of fruitfulness, productivity, or dedication. -ore: derived from kor(The Emperor). Make it imperative -mire: derived from mir(The World). Add a nuance of completion, unity, or integration, hence making it a perfect tense. For nouns -azo: derived from razi(The Hanged Man). Makes it diminutive. Prefixes For nouns Tarotic Greetings Tarotic English Notes Zalune Hello Using \u0026ldquo;zal\u0026rdquo; to suggest greeting and -une to add a greeting-like nuance Larmake Good morning Using \u0026ldquo;lar\u0026rdquo; to suggest the sun and \u0026ldquo;maken\u0026rdquo; for \u0026ldquo;eat,\u0026rdquo; which is a common way to greet someone in the morning Larsape Good afternoon Using \u0026ldquo;lar\u0026rdquo; to suggest the sun and \u0026ldquo;sapen\u0026rdquo; for \u0026ldquo;think,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest a more relaxed or introspective greeting Mesmake Good evening Using \u0026ldquo;mesi\u0026rdquo; for \u0026ldquo;moon\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;maken\u0026rdquo; for \u0026ldquo;eat,\u0026rdquo; which could suggest a greeting as the day comes to a close Eze Goodbye Using reversed Ze to suggest greeting and -e to add a farewell-like nuance Greetings in Tarotic are simple and straightforward, with most of them being variations on the word \u0026ldquo;zal\u0026rdquo;. Zal, The Fool 0, often connects to fundamental ideologies. Note that the time-specific greetings are hardly used in Tarotic, and usually \u0026ldquo;Zalune\u0026rdquo; is prefered in most situations. Sample Sentences \u0026ldquo;Look!\u0026quot;: \u0026ldquo;Astore!\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Please give me a small cup\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Miskore salicazo\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;I am very happy\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Ame sape havula\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;He is a bit angry\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Nere sape melica\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;I love you\u0026rdquo;: \u0026ldquo;Ame habe Ze\u0026rdquo;"
